## SOLID PRINCIPLES — WHEN AND HOW TO APPLY

### S — Single Responsibility
> Each class does ONE thing and has ONE reason to change.

- ✅ A use case only orchestrates one action
- ✅ An entity only holds business rules for that entity
- ❌ A controller that validates, queries DB, and sends emails

### O — Open/Closed
> Open for extension, closed for modification.

- ✅ Add a new payment method by creating a new class, not editing existing ones
- ✅ Use ports so you can swap implementations without touching core logic

### L — Liskov Substitution
> Any implementation of a port must work anywhere that port is expected.

- ✅ `UserRepositoryPostgres` and `UserRepositoryMongo` both implement `UserRepositoryPort` and behave consistently
- ❌ An implementation that throws unexpected errors or ignores contract methods

### I — Interface Segregation
> Don't force classes to implement methods they don't need.

- ✅ `ReadUserRepositoryPort` (findById, findAll) separate from `WriteUserRepositoryPort` (save, update, delete)
- ❌ One giant repository interface with 15 methods when you only need 2

### D — Dependency Inversion
> Depend on abstractions (ports), not on concrete implementations.

- ✅ Use case receives `UserRepositoryPort` — doesn't know if it's Postgres or Mongo
- ❌ Use case directly instantiates `new UserRepositoryPostgres()`

