## PATTERNS BY COMPLEXITY LEVEL

---

### LEVEL 1 — SMALL PROJECT

**Apply:** Entities, Use Cases, Ports, Controllers, Repositories, SOLID

#### ENTITY
```
// core/entities/user.entity.ts
// Plain class — no framework imports, no ORM annotations

Class User:
  PRIVATE id, name, email, active

  CONSTRUCTOR(id, name, email):
    validate name and email       // throws if invalid
    SET active = true

  METHOD deactivate():
    IF already inactive → throw error
    SET active = false

  PRIVATE validations:
    validateEmail → format check
    validateName  → not empty, minimum length
```

#### PORT
```
// core/ports/repositories/user.repository.port.ts
// Interface — defines WHAT is needed

INTERFACE UserRepositoryPort:
  findById(id)       → User | null
  findByEmail(email) → User | null
  save(user)         → void
  emailExists(email) → boolean
```

#### USE CASE
```
// core/use-cases/create-user.use-case.ts
// One action, one file, no HTTP, no DB

CLASS CreateUserUseCase:
  DEPENDS ON: UserRepositoryPort, EmailServicePort

  METHOD execute(name, email):
    IF emailExists → throw "Email already registered"
    user = new User(generateId(), name, email)
    repo.save(user)
    emailService.sendWelcome(user.email)
    RETURN { id, name, email }
```

#### CONTROLLER
```
// adapters/controllers/user.controller.ts
// Only translates: request → use case → response

CLASS UserController:
  METHOD create(request):
    TRY:
      result = createUserUseCase.execute(request.body)
      RETURN 201 with result
    CATCH error:
      RETURN 400 with error.message
```

---

### LEVEL 2 — MEDIUM PROJECT

**Apply everything from Level 1, plus:**
- Value Objects
- Result Pattern
- Domain Events

#### VALUE OBJECT
> Use when a concept has its own validation and has no identity of its own.
> Examples: Email, Money, Address, PhoneNumber, Coordinates

```
// core/value-objects/email.value-object.ts
// Immutable — once created, never changes

CLASS Email:
  PRIVATE value: string

  CONSTRUCTOR(raw: string):
    IF invalid format → throw "Invalid email format"
    SET value = raw.toLowerCase().trim()

  GETTER value → string
  METHOD equals(other: Email) → boolean
  METHOD toString() → string
```

> Now `User` uses `Email` instead of a plain string.
> Validation lives in the value object, not scattered everywhere.

#### RESULT PATTERN
> Use when a use case can fail for business reasons (not system crashes).
> Never throw exceptions for expected business failures.

```
// shared/result/result.ts

CLASS Result<T>:
  PRIVATE success: boolean
  PRIVATE value?: T
  PRIVATE error?: string

  STATIC ok(value: T)        → Result<T>   // success
  STATIC fail(error: string) → Result<T>   // business failure

  GETTER isSuccess → boolean
  GETTER isFailure → boolean
  GETTER getValue  → T        // throws if failure
  GETTER getError  → string   // throws if success
```

```
// Use case using Result Pattern
METHOD execute(name, email): Result<UserDTO>
  IF emailExists → RETURN Result.fail("Email already registered")

  user = new User(generateId(), name, new Email(email))
  repo.save(user)

  RETURN Result.ok({ id, name, email })
```

```
// Controller using Result
result = createUserUseCase.execute(data)
IF result.isFailure → RETURN 422 with result.getError
RETURN 201 with result.getValue
```

#### DOMAIN EVENT
> Use when something happens in the domain that other parts might care about.
> The entity emits the event — it doesn't know who listens.

```
// core/events/user-created.event.ts

CLASS UserCreatedEvent:
  userId: string
  email: string
  occurredAt: Date
```

```
// Entity emits event after something important happens
user.addDomainEvent(new UserCreatedEvent(user.id, user.email))
```

```
// adapters/event-handlers/send-welcome-email.handler.ts
// Listens and reacts — completely decoupled from the use case

CLASS SendWelcomeEmailHandler:
  HANDLES: UserCreatedEvent

  METHOD handle(event):
    emailService.sendWelcome(event.email)
```

