## IMPORT RULES

### ✅ ALLOWED
```
Infrastructure → Adapters → Core
Use Cases → Entities, Value Objects, Ports, Events
Event Handlers → Domain Events (only the event class)
```

### ❌ FORBIDDEN
```
Core → Adapters or Infrastructure
Core → any framework or database library
Entities → other entities or use cases
One bounded context's core → another bounded context's core
```

---

## UBIQUITOUS LANGUAGE

> Code must speak the language of the business.
> If the business says "place an order", the code says `PlaceOrderCommand`, not `CreateOrderRequest`.
> If the business says "confirm", the method is `confirm()`, not `setStatusToConfirmed()`.

Rules:
- Class and method names come from the business vocabulary
- If a developer and a domain expert can read the code together and understand it — you got it right
- Avoid technical terms in the domain layer: no `DTO`, no `Model`, no `Entity` suffix inside core logic — those are for infrastructure

---

## DECISION GUIDE — WHICH PATTERN TO USE

| Situation | Pattern to Apply |
|-----------|-----------------|
| Object with its own validation and no identity | Value Object |
| Something happened that others might care about | Domain Event |
| Operation can fail for business reasons | Result Pattern |
| Reads and writes have very different complexity | CQRS |
| Multiple entities managed as a unit | Aggregate |
| System has 3+ independent domains | Bounded Contexts |
| Multi-step process across domains with failure recovery | Saga |
| You need to swap implementations without touching logic | Port + Adapter |

---

## WHAT NOT TO DO

- ❌ Don't add CQRS to a project with 3 entities
- ❌ Don't create Value Objects for every string — only when validation and immutability matter
- ❌ Don't emit Domain Events for every property change — only for meaningful business moments
- ❌ Don't put business logic in controllers or repositories
- ❌ Don't import framework decorators inside `core/`
- ❌ Don't share entities between bounded contexts — duplicate and translate
- ❌ Don't create a Saga for a two-step process — a use case is enough
